Bake for 20 minutes. After 20 minutes, remove the lid and lower the oven temperature to 475 degrees. Bake for another 15 to 25 minutes until the bread is golden brown. my oven seems to trap in a moisture. Raising your own meat chickens, whether it's Freedom Rangers or other breeds, can provide several benefits: 1. Quality control: When you raise your own meat chickens, you have complete control over their diet and living conditions. You can choose to feed them high-quality, organic feed, ensuring that they are raised in a healthy and sustainable manner. This allows you to have better control over the quality of the meat you and your family consume. 2. Cost savings: Raising your own meat chickens can be more cost-effective in the long run. While there are initial setup costs such as housing and equipment, the ongoing expenses can be lower compared to purchasing meat from the store. By producing your own chicken meat, you can save on the markup and transportation costs associated with store-bought meat. 3. Healthier and safer meat: By raising your own meat chickens, you have the assurance of knowing exactly how they were raised and what they were fed. This enables you to avoid antibiotics, hormones, and other potentially harmful additives that are sometimes found in commercially raised poultry. You can prioritize their well-being and ensure the highest standards of food safety. 4. Connection to your food: Raising your own meat chickens can provide a deeper connection to your food and the process of raising animals for sustenance. It allows you to have a better understanding and appreciation for where your food comes from, fostering a sense of self-sufficiency and satisfaction in knowing that you played a role in providing for your family's needs. 5. Environmental impact: Raising your own meat chickens on a small scale can be more environmentally friendly compared to large-scale commercial farming. You can implement sustainable practices such as using their manure as fertilizer for your garden, utilizing pasture-based systems, and reducing the carbon footprint associated with transportation and packaging. 6. Educational experience: Raising meat chickens can be an educational experience for both adults and children. It offers an opportunity to learn about animal husbandry, responsibility, and the cycle of life. It can also be a great way to teach children about where their food comes from and instill values of self-sufficiency and sustainability. #homestead #farmlife #hardmeadfarm #raisingchickens #butchertiktok #savingmoney #food #chicken #freedomrangers #freerange #pastureraised

To plant tomatoes, follow these steps: 1. Choose a suitable location: Select a sunny spot in your garden with well-draining soil. 2. Prepare the soil: Dig a hole that is deep enough to accommodate the tomato plant's root ball. Loosen the soil and add organic matter like compost or well-rotted manure to enrich it. I also like to add an egg.  3. Planting the tomato: Gently remove the tomato plant from its container, being careful not to damage the roots. Place the plant in the hole, ensuring that the top of the root ball is level with or slightly above the soil surface. 4. Pinch off side stems: To encourage strong growth, remove the lower side stems or "suckers" by pinching them off. This allows the plant to focus its energy on producing fruit. 5. Planting deeply or in a trench: If your tomato plant is tall or leggy, you can plant it deeply by burying a portion of the stem in the soil. Alternatively, you can plant it in a trench by laying the stem horizontally in a shallow trench and covering it with soil, leaving only the top portion of the plant exposed. 6. Mound slightly: After planting, gently mound soil around the base of the plant. This helps stabilize the plant and provides additional support. 7. Water thoroughly: Give your newly planted tomato a good watering, ensuring that the soil is evenly moist. Water regularly, especially during dry spells, to keep the soil consistently moist but not waterlogged. 8. Mulch: Apply a layer of organic mulch, such as straw or wood chips, around the base of the plant to help conserve moisture, suppress weeds, and regulate soil temperature. Remember to provide support, such as stakes or cages, as the tomato plant grows to keep it upright. Regularly monitor for pests and diseases, and provide proper care, including regular watering and fertilization, to ensure healthy tomato plants and a bountiful harvest. #hardmeadfarm #homemaking #gardening #howtoplanttomatos #homestead #tomatoes #food #growsomething #growing #gardeningtips #growyourownfood

Ingredients: - 950g flour - 200g active sourdough starter - 650g water - 20g salt Instructions: 1. In a large mixing bowl, combine the water and active sourdough starter. Mix well to ensure the starter is fully incorporated into the water. 2. Gradually add the flour to the wet mixture. Stir continuously until the dough begins to come together.  3. Sprinkle the salt evenly over the dough mixture and continue to mix until all ingredients are well combined. 4. Once the dough is fully mixed, cover the bowl with a clean kitchen towel and let it rest for 30 minutes. This allows the dough to hydrate and develop gluten. 5. After the resting period, perform a series of stretch and folds to strengthen the dough. Gently stretch one side of the dough up and fold it over the center. Repeat this process for each side of the dough, rotating the bowl as needed. Complete the stretch and fold process for about 2-4 sets.  6. Cover the bowl again and let the dough ferment at room temperature for 8-12 hours, or until it has doubled in size. This slow fermentation process enhances the flavor and texture of the bread. 7. Once the dough has doubled in size, it is ready for shaping. Carefully transfer the dough onto a lightly floured surface. Divide it into two equal portions and shape each portion into a loaf.  8. Place shaped dough into baskets or small bowels lined with flour sack towels. Cover and leave to rise on the counter for 4 hours or in the fridge for up to a few days.   9. Preheat your oven to 500¬∞F during the final 30 minutes of the rising time. 10. Once the loaves have risen, score the top of each loaf with a sharp knife or razor blade to allow for controlled expansion during baking. 11. Place the loaves in the preheated Dutch oven and bake for 20 minutes, remove lid and back at 475¬∞ for a further 15mins.  12. Once baked, remove the loaves from the oven and let them cool on a wire rack before slicing. Enjoy your freshly baked homemade sourdough bread! text: Title: Roasted Butternut Squash with a spicy Creamy Twist Ingredients: - 1 butternut squash, about 1kg, peeled and deseeded - 2 tbsp olive oil - 1 tbsp butter - 2 onions, diced - 1 garlic clove, thinly sliced - 2 mild red chillies, deseeded and finely chopped - 850ml hot vegetable stock - 1/2 cup of raw cream, plus more to serve Instructions: 1. Preheat your oven to 200¬∞C (400¬∞F). 2. Cut the peeled and deseeded butternut squash into small, uniform cubes. 3. Place the cubed butternut squash on a baking sheet and drizzle with olive oil. Toss the squash to coat it evenly with the oil. 4. Bake the butternut squash in the preheated oven for approximately 30 minutes, or until it is fork-tender and lightly golden. 5. In the meantime, heat the butter in a large pot or saucepan over medium heat. 6. Add the diced onions, thinly sliced garlic, and finely chopped chillies to the pot. Saut√© until the onions are translucent and fragrant. 7. Once the butternut squash is roasted, remove it from the oven and let it cool slightly. 8. Transfer the roasted squash to the pot with the onion mixture, and stir well to combine. 9. Pour in the hot vegetable stock, ensuring that the squash is fully submerged. Bring the mixture to a gentle boil. 10. Reduce the heat to low and let the soup simmer for about 20-25 minutes, or until the butternut squash is tender and easily mashed with a fork. 11. Remove the pot from the heat and allow the soup to cool slightly. 12. Using an immersion blender or a regular blender, puree the soup until smooth and creamy. 13. Return the pot to low heat and stir in the cr√®me fra√Æche. Heat the soup gently until it is warmed through. 14. Serve the creamy butternut squash soup in bowls, topped with a dollop of raw cream. Optionally, garnish with a sprinkle of fresh herbs or a drizzle of olive oil.
